<F P=106> [Report by C. Molusi] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria March 24 SAPA -- The Freedom Front [FF] 
said on Thursday [24 March] it was ironic that the National 
Party [NP] was suddenly concerned about the number of communists 
on the African National Congress' [ANC] election candidates list. 
  Reacting to Foreign Affairs Minister Pik Botha's statement 
that more than half of the people in the top 50 of the ANC's 
list were communists, the Freedom Front said it was the NP that 
had declared communism dead when it unbanned the SA [South 
African] Communist Party [SACP] in 1990. 
  Mr Botha was responding to a challenge by SACP official 
Jeremy Cronin that the NP should prove the SACP had more than 16 
members on the ANC list. 
  Freedom Front leader Constand Viljoen said his party 
remained 
consistent in its opposition to communism, and urged voters to 
support the FF to effectively combat the communist threat. 

