<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Favorable View of NP in Western Cape </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2503072394 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1800 
GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2503072394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A preelection snap poll done for the SABC [South 
African Broadcasting Corporation] by Markinor gives some idea of 
how election campaigns are going down in the Western Cape. A 
representative sample of 400 people of all races throughout the 
province was interviewed earlier this month. 
  The poll found that the National Party [NP] and its leader, 
F.W. de Klerk, had quite favorable images among the Western Cape 
electorate as whole, and they are the strongest among coloreds. 
Sixty-one percent of all potential voters see the NP favorably, 
as do 74 percent of colored voters. 
  The ANC [African National Congress] and its leader, Nelson 
Mandela, have fairly unfavorable images in the same area except 
among the African minority. Both major party candidates for 
provincial premier are unpopular. Only 12 percent think the 
NP's Hernus Kriel would make a good premier, while 21 percent 
think the ANC's Allan Boesak would. The poll found that the 
issues having the most impact in the Western Cape campaign 
concerned group identity and economic benefits. These include 
fears of how an ANC government would treat coloreds and whites, 
and whether coloreds identify with whites or with blacks. 
Overall, the survey found that 37 percent of potential Western 
Cape voters say the National Party could best handle what they 
consider the most important issues. Twenty percent named the 
ANC, 7 percent the Democratic Party, and 2 percent the 
Pan-Africanist Congress. 

</TEXT>

