<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Responds to Latest UNITA Demands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2503053194 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2503053194 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Another plenary session has been postponed in 
Lusaka, Zambia. The session was expected to examine the 
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola's [UNITA] 
reply presented to the mediator yesterday. Our correspondent in 
Lusaka, Joao Ligio reports. 
  The new document presented by UNITA asks for the 
continuation 
of the Voice of Resistance of the Black Cockerel's [Vorgan] 
broadcasts on shortwave, the return of its property in good 
condition, and the granting of party installations and houses 
for its leaders. UNITA also announced the introduction of a new 
list of its 70 deputies. 
  The government, which was expected to give its official 
reaction had the plenary session had taken place, said that 
Vorgan Radio should operate on shortwave only until December. 
Thereafter, it should join other medium wave national broadcasts. 
  On the return of property, the government says: Give me what 
is mine, and you will have what is yours. If you impose 
conditions on what is mine, you will receive equal treatment. 
  On the granting of party installations and houses for UNITA 
leaders, the government referred to the law regulating the 
acquisition of immovable property in the country. 
  On the new list of UNITA deputies, the government wants to 
know the fate of those who in parliament speak in the name of 
UNITA. 
  What is strange is that this document does not mention the 
debate over ministries and provinces. This could mean the 
parties are making progress in this direction. According to 
UNITA's Jorge Valentim, his delegation accepts the government's 
offer of the Ministries of Health, Tourism and Hotel Industry, 
and Public Works. The Public Works Ministry will still be 
debated, in view of its nonexistence. Jorge Valentim said UNITA 
accepts the Provinces of Uige, Lunda Sul, and Cuando Cubango, 
and it is presently negotiating the Provinces of Benguela and 
Huambo, which the government says are negotiable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

