<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   IRNA Cites Opposition Radio on Missing `Classified' Discs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2703154694 Tehran IRNA in English 1510 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2703154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, March 27, IRNA -- Loss of floppy diskettes 
containing vital classified information has terrified the Iraqi 
regime, according to radio 'Voice of the Iraqi People', 
monitored here today. 
  The radio said Iraq security forces have started inspecting 
houses of hundreds of persons suspected of removing the 
diskettes, and have arrested a number of employees of related 
departments. 
  It has not yet been clarified what data the diskettes 
contained, but the way the Iraqi regime is treating the 
suspects, the radio said it is likely that they might contain 
vital security information. 
  What's more concerning for the regime is that foreign 
embassies in Baghdad can get access to the diskettes. 
  The radio added that broadcast of the classified information 
contained in the diskettes by internationl radio stations might 
also be critical for the Iraqi regime. 
  Voice of the Iraqi People is an opposition radio operating 
from somewhere inside Iraq. It did not give further details. 

</TEXT>

