<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Denounces Clinton's Remarks on Jerusalem </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN2603133294 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0810 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN2603133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 26 Mar (INA)--The newspaper AL-'IRAQ has 
denounced U.S. President Bill Clinton's recent statements in 
which he announced before the leaders of Jewish organizations in 
the United States that he and his government consider Jerusalem 
as the united capital of the Zionist entity. 
  In an article today, the paper notes: During his election 
campaign, Clinton competed with his predecessor George Bush to 
win Zionist votes by pledging never to forsake the Zionist 
entity. 
  The paper points out that this pledge included Clinton's 
readiness to support the Zionist entity by giving it loans and 
grants to finance the establishment of settlements in the 
occupied West Bank, and assurances that the Zionists will not 
find a better friend at times of war or peace. 
  The paper reviews some of Clinton's actions after he won the 
presidential elections. The most important of these actions are 
his disavowal of the statement in which he expressed his 
readiness to turn over a new leaf in relations with Iraq if Iraq 
complied with the UN Security Council resolutions, his missile 
attack on Baghdad, and the current scandals in which he and his 
family are involved. 
  The paper notes that the campaign against Clinton's 
reputation by the Republicans and certain Zionists is due to the 
fact that these circles are not satisfied with the White House 
President merely announcing openly that he supports the Zionist 
entity, they want him to prove, through words and deeds, that he 
will pursue this course, and show that any deviation from this 
course will result in blackmailing and exposing him, making him 
a lesson to others. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

