<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TEC Considering State of Emergency in Natal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2903154794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1418 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2903154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by P Bulger] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria March 29 SAPA -- The Transitional Executive 
Council [TEC] was looking into greater security force powers 
that would amount to a state of emergency being declared in 
Natal/kwaZulu. TEC Executive Secretary Mac Maharaj told the TEC 
on Tuesday [29 March] that security force action had already 
been stepped up in the territory as violence continued to 
escalate. He said the TEC's law and order sub-council was 
devising regulations to give security forces greater powers. 
These regulations would mean declaring unrest areas or a state 
of emergency in the province, Mr Maharaj said. The actions were 
intended to secure a free and fair election in the territory. 
  The TEC resolution commits the TEC to co-operating with the 
security forces and the South African Government in intensified 
security operations to secure free and fair elections in 
Natal/kwaZulu. The TEC mandated its joint executive secretaries 
and its sub-council on law and order to "interact with 
governmental structures in the drafting of regulations providing 
special powers for the security forces needed to secure the 
safety of voters, the election process and reasonable 
electioneering through party- political activity". The 
resolution recommends in principle that "as soon as may be 
necessary these regulations be put into operation in 
kwaZulu/Natal, under the legislation that may be appropriate at 
that time, that is the declaration of a state of emergency or of 
unrest areas". The TEC said the special powers would be kept 
under constant review by the government, the TEC and the 
Independent Electoral Commission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-1508 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr061_c_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-061 </AU>
