<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on TEC Deliberations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB3003121894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1051 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB3003121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg March 30 SAPA -- The Transitional 
Executive Council [TEC] was going ahead with arrangements to 
declare a state of emergency in Natal/kwaZulu, a TEC source said 
on Wednesday [30 March]. The emergency will remain an option for 
the TEC and President F W de Klerk if the security situation 
continues to deteriorate in the province and if political 
initiatives fail to produce results. The other option is the 
declaration of unrest areas in selected magisterial districts. 
  The TEC on Tuesday agreed in principle to a state of 
emergency to ensure that election preparations went ahead and 
that the security situation was stabilised. Troops were already 
being deployed on an "incremental basis". 
  The TEC's Law and Order Sub-Council, TEC legal advisers and 
government representatives were meeting in Pretoria on Wednesday 
afternoon to draw up the regulations in terms of the public 
safety act. 
  The preparations would be completed by Thursday afternoon, 
putting President de Klerk in a position to introduce at the 
stroke of his pen draconian security measures last seen in the 
province when the state of emergency there was lifted in October 
1990. 
  The TEC source said there would be a state of emergency 
"unless there is major movement on the political front". 
  "The emergency will be held as a sword of Damocles over 
kwaZulu," the source said. 
  Meanwhile, negotiating teams representing the African 
National Congress and the Inkatha Freedom Party were due to meet 
in Johannesburg on Wednesday afternoon to put the finishing 
touches to preparations for international mediation to resolve 
their outstanding constitutional differences. The mediation 
process could get underway next week. 
  And the four-sided summit involving President de Klerk, ANC 
President Nelson Mandela, IFP President Mangosuthu Buthelezi and 
Zulu King Goodwill Zwelithini is due to take place next week. 
  The TEC source said the emergency regulations may be held in 
abeyance until the outcome of the summit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

