<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peacekeeping Force To Cost 384.5 Million Rands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB3003095194 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 0500 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB3003095194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The National Peace Keeping Force [NPKF] is to cost 
the taxpayer a total of 384.5 million rands, 315 million rands 
less than expected. This was revealed at a TEC [Transitional 
Executive Council] meeting in Pretoria yesterday, when the 
details of the budget of the NPKF was announced for the 
1994-1995 financial year. The budget from 1 April this year 
until 30 June, is 255 million rands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-1517 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr061_c_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   South African Press Review for 29 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2903143694 </F>
<F P=103> MB2903143694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] 
<H6>  THE CITIZEN </H6>
  ANC To Escalate Mass Action in kwaZulu/Natal--Johannesburg 
THE CITIZEN in English on 28 March in its page-6 editorial notes 
that according to pollsters "there is no doubt that the ANC 
[African National Congress] will win hands down -- and might 
even get a two-thirds majority. Sadly, the ANC has become 
arrogant and intolerant." ANC Secretary General Cyril Ramaphosa 
has announced that the ANC would "escalate its rolling mass 
action" in kwaZulu/Natal "until Chief Buthelezi guarantees free 
political activity in the region. The danger that the low-key 
civil war there could flare into a full-scale conflict does not 
worry the ANC -- it is not going to give up its plan to topple 
Chief Buthelezi and it will proceed whatever the consequences." 
<H6>  THE STAR </H6>
  State May Have To Consider State of Emergency -- Referring 
to 
the violence that erupted in the wake of the Zulu rally in 
Johannesburg on 28 March, Johannesburg THE STAR in English on 29 
March in a page-14 editorial says: "Any parties, or leaders 
playing a political role -- as Zulu King Goodwill Zwelithini is 
playing in this period -- have to ask themselves two questions 
among others. First, will our planned action have the 
effect of being provocative, and placing lives at risk? It 
is no defence to say this was not the intention. Second, have 
we ensured that none of our supporters is armed? Again, it is 
not good enough to say one didn't know. If political leaders -- 
from whatever party -- are not prepared to honour these basic 
responsibilities, then they invite inevitable illiberal censure: 
the temporary prohibition of some or all high-risk 
demonstrations." "A reversion to state of emergency politics 
would inevitably open the door to political abuse, and it would 
tragically mar the birth of the new South Africa. But if 
politicians are so cynical as to actively explore the Bosnia 
option, then it is a step that might have to be considered." 
  Only SADF Can Impose Free Political Activity in Natal -- A 
second editorial on the same page believes that if all else 
fails "one thing would stand between South Africa and a descent 
into utter chaos -- the presence of an effective and apolitical 
Defence Force." The South African Defense Force (SADF) has been 
called on recently to restore order in Bophuthatswana, Ciskei, 
and Lebowa. "The SADF could yet face its stiffest challenge in 
kwaZulu. As matters there deteriorate, pressure is building up 
for a deployment of troops. Both ANC secretary-general Cyril 
Ramaphosa and the organisation's kwaZulu/Natal premiership 
candidate, Jacob Zuma, have called on the TEC [Transitional 
Executive Council] to send troops into the region. It is no 
longer a far-fetched prospect, and nor is it one to relish. But 
if free political activity has to be imposed, only the SADF can 
do it." 
<H6>  BUSINESS DAY </H6>
  Attempts To Overthrow Kwazulu To Have `Horrendous Costs' -- 
Johannesburg BUSINESS DAY in English on 29 March in a page-16 
editorial also refers to the rally "called by traditional Zulu 
leaders in support of their king." 
  "The Johannesburg chaos, it should be noted, was not 
exceptional compared with the violence that has afflicted black 
residential communities on the East and West Rand, and in many 
parts of Natal, with the loss of thousands of lives. Strife of 
this magnitude rarely comes to the city centres, so for those 
not used to life in the townships it was particularly alarming." 
The events in Johannesburg "are evidence that ANC attempts to 
overthrow kwaZulu Chief Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi, and 
Buthelezi's apparent resistance to a political settlement which 
may cost him his office, will have horrendous costs, possibly 
more than the economy can afford. The election must go ahead. 
But the chances of it being universally free and fair are 
declining. And it is almost too late to halt the spiral." 
<H6>  SOWETAN </H6>
  Editorial Blames IFP for Johannesburg Rally Violence -- 
Johannesburg SOWETAN in English on 29 March in a page-8 
editorial places the blame for the deaths linked to the protest 
march in Johannesburg "squarely on the leadership of the Inkatha 
Freedom Party [IFP]. Nobody is fooled by people changing names 
at the drop of a hat -- one minute they are IFP leaders and the 
next they are `Zulus' protesting rather strenuously that they 
are not speaking for the IFP." SOWETAN also believes the 
violence "could only have been premeditated. First, there has 
been war talk from the leadership of the IFP; then there was the 
turning of a blind eye on the weapons that were displayed during 
the march; and finally there was the glaring absence of marshals 
to control the huge crowds." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-1518 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr061_c_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   South African Press Review for 30 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB3003103094 </F>
<F P=103> MB3003103094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] 
<H6>  THE STAR </H6>
  Advance for Democracy -- "The decision by Transkei's 
military 
regime to allow the National Party [NP] to open offices in the 
homeland is belated but welcome. There ought never to have been 
any question about the NP Operating in Transkei. That is the 
democratic right of all parties," notes an editorial in 
Johannesburg THE STAR in English on 30 March on page 18. "The 
ANC [African National Congress] and its allies have been enraged 
by Buthelezi's resistance to allowing his opponents to organise 
or even to help faciliate the right to vote in the April 
election," but they have remained "conspicuously silent about 
their `favored militay dictators' Holomisa" and Ramushwana of 
Venda. "A similiar reticence marks their attitude to corruption 
in Lebowa and kwaNdebele." "The use of South African troops to 
help srabilise" the government in Qwaqwa "is another welcome 
development. It shows that the SADF [South African Defense 
Force] is capable pf pre-emptive stabilising action, and will 
not be called upon to mop up once violence has already run its 
course." 
<H6>  BUSINESS DAY </H6>
  A Fateful Choice -- "Monday's events in Johannesburg in 
which 
more than 30 Zulu royalists were killed, must fall into the same 
category as the shootings at Boipatong and Bisho and the 
assassination of Chris Hani, as far as their impact on the 
transition process is concerned," an editorial in Johannesburg 
BUSINESS DAY in English on 30 March on page 14 states. "Each of 
these events had the potential to derail the process," but each 
also produced a "countervailing force -- prompting renewed and 
more determined efforts." "The same two possible scenarios lie 
ahead now -- intensified conflict or a new successful phase of 
negotiations." "It is becoming increasingly apparent that an 
election in Natal can be no more than a stopgap measure, if 
that. A comprehensive political settelemnt before the end of 
April is impossible." "Even though Inkatha does not have a hope 
of winning a `struggle to the end,' it doubtless has the ability 
-- like Angola's UNITA [National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola] or Mozambique's Renamo [Mozambique 
National Resistance] -- to hamper or even render impossible 
South Africa's attempts to democratise and develop." The ANC, 
NP and others "might be on the point of deciding that the only 
way to secure a relatively free election is to neutralise 
Inkatha now through mass action, emergency rule and, ultimately, 
brute force. No one dare take that fateful step before every 
other action is tried." 
<H6>  SOWETAN </H6>
  Postmortems -- The "finger pointing" and postmortems 
concerning the "spectacular" events in Johannesburg have already 
begun, notes an editorial in Johannesburg SOWETAN in English on 
30 March on page 10. "Two important things can result from the 
event. The first is that the security situation before the 
elections has got to be tightened up and made more effective. 
The second is the calling of the summit of major political 
leaders." "We are afraid the time for political point-scoring is 
fast becoming real" and we are "sickened by the manner in which 
ordinary people are used in a battle for power that has very 
little to do with the future of South Africa." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

