<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Second-Round Elections Under Discussion at Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2903194994 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2903194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Lusaka, the mediators and the observers are still 
trying to reach an agreement on various issues that separate 
negotiators from the government and the National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola [UNITA]. The ad hoc commission has 
been meeting behind closed door. Our correspondent Pedro Manuel 
reports from Lusaka. 
  Good evening! The Ad Hoc Commission for the Conclusion of 
the 
Electoral Process continues to work for an agreement. What the 
negotiators are doing is to define all issues connected with the 
second round of presidential elections. So far, there is total 
secrecy and nothing is known about the discussions, although 
observers feel this issue will be easy to resolve. 
  This afternoon, while the commission was carrying out its 
work, the remaining members of delegations from the government 
and UNITA decided to meet alone, without third parties, 
somewhere here in Lusaka. The objective of the meeting is not 
known, but this is not new. Even in Abidjan, during situations 
of impasse, the delegations met at secret venues in search of an 
agreement. Taking this into account, it is very probable that 
today's meeting was connected with the country's governance. 
Although the parties are presently working on the conclusion of 
the electoral process, the truth is that there is an impasse 
with regard to the country's governance. 

</TEXT>

