<F P=101> Central African Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Patasse Signs Business Law Treaty With Senegal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB3003174594 Bangui Radiodiffusion-Television Centrafricaine 
Radio in French 1800 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB3003174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangui Radiodiffusion-Television Centrafricaine 
Radio </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Summary From Poor Reception] "President Felix 
Ange-Patasse this morning signed a treaty on the harmonization 
of business law in Africa." Senegal was represented by "Justice 
Minister Jacques Baudin, who is Senegalese President Abdou 
Diouf's special envoy. The ceremony took place at the 
Renaissance Palace in the presence of Prime Minister Jean-Luc 
Mandaba, government officials, and the head of state's adviser. 
The signing of this treaty took place a few hours after the 
head of state received the Senegalese minister. On this 
occasion, President Felix Ange-Patasse made a statement in which 
he touched on the importance of true African integration." 
  [Begin Patasse recording] "Mr. Minister and special envoy 
from my brother, President Abdou Diouf, we receive you here 
today joyfully to sign this treaty on the harmonization of 
business law in Africa. We are now signing this treaty, because 
the Central African Republic was absent at the CFA franc zone 
talks held on the sidelines of the francophone summit in 
Mauritius. During our visit. During our visit to Dakar, 
President Abdou Diouf asked me if he could send the minister of 
justice" to sign this treaty, which is one of the elements which 
can promote cooperation among African countries. "We have 
signed this treaty because we believe in the real integration of 
Africa." There are clauses that must disappear because 
businessmen cannot settle in this or that country because their 
respective laws are not the same or because these laws portray 
nationalistic feelings. "African countries are faced with 
difficulties because they do not have complementary 
legislation." The moment has come for Africans to unite. 
Europe is united. The United States is united. Asia is 
united. But Africa is always late. Instead of giving priority 
to consultations and dialogue for a real takeoff, we are groping 
around. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

