<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zaire </F>
<H3> <TI>   HCR-PT Adopts New `Constitutional Act' on Transition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB3003231394 Paris AFP in French 2233 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB3003231394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kinshasa, 31 Mar [date as received] (AFP)--The High 
Council of the Republic-Transitional Parliament [HCR-PT] this 
evening adopted a completely new "constitutional act" for 
governing Zaire's democratic transition towards the Third 
Republic. 
  This particular act defines relations between the government 
and the Presidency of the Republic and also entrusts the HCR-PT 
with the task of overseeing the government's activities. It 
fixes the duration of the transition at 15 months, during which 
time a constitutional referendum, as well as presidential and 
legislative elections, must be organized. The Parliament 
earlier on had adopted Article 76 of this act, over which the 
presidential group and the radical opposition had been divided 
for the past seven months. 
  The Sacred Union of the Radical Opposition, USOR, did not 
succeed in having Mr. Etienne Tshisekedi recognized as the legal 
prime minister, because he was elected by the Sovereign National 
Conference, CNS. The conditions for the appointment of a prime 
minister do not make any reference to the CNS, but simply say 
that he must be appointed by the opposition "after consultation 
with the political class." 
  Several members of the USOR delegation left the HCR/PT in 
protest, and three of them were expelled from the room for 
disorderly behavior. Since voting was carried out by a raising 
of hands, it was not possible know which members of the various 
parties forming the USOR voted for the adoption of the text, 
which was contested by the hardliners of the radical opposition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

