<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Uganda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Citizens Vote in Constituent Assembly Elections </TI></H3>
<H4>   Museveni Supporters Said Faring Well </H4>
<F P=102> EA3003144394 Dar es Salaam Radio Tanzania External Service 
in English 1000 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA3003144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Dar es Salaam Radio Tanzania External Service 
in English 1000 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Supporters of President Yoweri Museveni secured an 
early strong showing in Uganda's first true experiment with 
democracy. With more than 20 percent of ballots counted from 
Monday's [28 March] votes for a new assembly, government 
ministers had good backing and Museveni supporters fared 
particularly well in south and southwest. President Museveni 
did not stand for any of the 214 seats in a new Constituent 
Assembly. 
  The commissioner of elections, Mr. Stephen Akabwai, said 
voting was continuing yesterday in Iganga and Kabarole 
Districts, the only ones which failed to complete polling on 
Monday out of 39 across the country. He said there were no 
major problems in the other areas and voting went on safely, 
adding that he expected results for more than half of the 
country to be compiled by yesterday evening and a complete list 
by today. 
  Nominators said President Museveni's supporters did 
unexpectedly well in the east, traditionally a stronghold of the 
opposition. 

</TEXT>

