<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA Negotiators Demand New Electoral Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB3003125694 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 1200 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB3003125694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] National Union for the Total Independence of Angola 
[UNITA] and Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola-Labor 
Party experts are meeting at the Mulungushi Conference Center in 
Lusaka for the second consecutive day today to discuss issues 
relating to the second round of Angola's presidential elections. 
Yesterday, the sides met on their own. Today's meeting is being 
mediated by the United Nations. 
  UNITA has already submitted a document to Alioune Blondin 
Beye calling for the replacement of the National Electoral 
Council [CNE] which conducted the September 1992 elections. A 
UNITA diplomatic source said this issue is not negotiable. 
UNITA has also asked for a more substantial and [words 
indistinct] role for the United Nations and a larger UNITA 
participation in the new CNE. Once this issue is dealt with, the 
negotiations will tackle national reconciliation, the future 
status of the president of UNITA -- the largest opposition party 
-- and the reciprocal return of property owned by the warring 
sides. 

</TEXT>

