<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   ULIMO Affirms Readiness To Accept ECOMOG Deployment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB3103111594 Monrovia Radio ELBC in English 0900 GMT 31 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> AB3103111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Monrovia Radio ELBC </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The ULIMO [United Liberation Movement for Democracy 
in Liberia] High Command says it is willing and ready to accept 
the deployment of ECOMOG [Economic Community of West African 
States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group] in Tubmanburg and other 
areas as part of the disarmament process provided this will be 
done simultaneously in other parts of the country. 
  The ULIMO field commander, General Mohamed Dumbuya, 
addressing a news conference on Monday [28 March] in Tubmanburg, 
said ULIMO is fully committed to the ongoing peace process and 
said they want the deployment of ECOMOG troops to be done 
simultaneously so that no one side will be put at a disadvantage. 
  The LIBERIAN NEWS AGENCY [LINA] correspondent who traveled 
to 
Tubmanburg quoted Gen. Dumbuya as saying that ULIMO will do 
nothing to jeopardize the current peace process and regretted 
the current infighting which is causing more hardships for the 
residents. Gen. Dumbuya said Bomi, Lower Lofa, and Grand Cape 
Mount Counties are now calm and he appealed to humanitarian 
organizations to resume relief operations in those areas. 
  The LINA correspondent said residents of Tubmanburg are 
yearning for deployment of ECOMOG troops in the city, 
considering the hardship being experienced in that area. The 
correspondent says Tubmanburg is hard hit by acute shortage of 
food, drugs, and other medical supplies as a result of the 
recent fighting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

