<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army: France Preparing To Intervene in Bakassi Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB3103110594 Lagos NTA Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB3103110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lagos NTA Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Nigerian Army says it has uncovered the real 
objective behind the recently concluded Franco-Beninese joint 
military exercise. A statement from the director of Army public 
relations says the level of participation and the manner in 
which the weeklong exercise was conducted showed that it was a 
preparation by France to eventually intervene on the side of 
Cameroon should the Bakassi dispute escalate. 
  The statement said about 544 officers including four 
colonels, two lieutenant colonels, and three majors left France 
with a lot of sophisticated armament and weapon systems for the 
exercise, and that some of the weapons were left in Benin 
Republic at the end, parts of which could be diverted to 
Cameroon for possible use against Nigeria. The Army says that 
military observers from neighboring countries including Nigeria, 
who were invited to witness the exercise, were not given any 
chance to see the arms and equipment used but were encouraged in 
tourism and ceremonial matters. 
  The statement points out what it called the clandestine and 
questionable role of France in the Nigeria-Cameroon problem as 
against Nigeria's genuine efforts toward a peaceful resolution 
of the conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

