<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Singapore Premier Leaves for Working Visit to China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2602045894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0420 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2602045894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Singapore, February 26 (XINHUA) -- Singapore Prime 
Minister Goh Chok Tong left here today for Beijing on a two-day 
working visit to China. 
  During his stay in Beijing, the prime minister and the 
Chinese Premier Li Peng are to attend and witness the signing of 
the Suzhou software transfer agreement. 
  The agreement will be signed by Singapore Senior Minister 
Lee 
Kuan Yew, who arrived in Beijing on Friday [25 February], and 
Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing. 
  The Suzhou project is believed to be the largest cooperation 
project so far between the two governments. 
  According to the agreement between the two countries, 
Singapore will invest a total of 20 billion U.S. dollars in the 
next 10-15 years to develop an industrial town covering 70 
square kilometers in Suzhou, and transfer Singapore's economic 
development and management experiences to Suzhou, a medium-sized 
city near Shanghai. 
  Lee Kuan Yew said here on Tuesday to XINHUA that the reason 
why Singapore chose Suzhou to be the venue of the joint 
government project is because Suzhou is located in the Chang 
Jiang delta and close to Shanghai, the dragon's head of the 
Chang Jiang valley, one of the fastest developing areas in China. 
  Lee said the prospects of the Suzhou project are "good," 
adding that though a well planned township in Suzhou would 
proceed at a slower pace than Shenzhen, "the long-term results 
will be better." 
  According to a press statement from the Prime Minister's 
Office, Goh Chok Tong and Lee Kuan Yew will meet Chinese leaders 
during their stay in Beijing. 
  During the prime minister's absence, Deputy Prime Minister 
Lee Hsieng Loong will be the acting prime minister, the 
statement said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

