<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Speaks at Signing Ceremony </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702133694 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1417 
GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2702133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 26 Feb (XINHUA) -- The Governments of 
China and Singapore signed an agreement on joint construction 
and development of the Suzhou Industrial Park here this 
afternoon. 
  Premier of the State Council Li Peng and Goh Chok Tong, 
Singapore's premier who is in China for a working visit, 
attended the signing ceremony. Vice Premier Li Lanqing and 
Singapore's Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew signed the agreement. 
  Under the agreement, both sides support Suzhou Municipality 
and the Singapore development consortium's cooperation in 
building and developing the Suzhou industrial park. The area 
for the first-phase development is eight square km. The project 
is designed to develop a modern industrial park of considerable 
size, with new and high technology as the leading sectors and 
modern industries as the main structure; other supplementary 
tertiary industry and social public welfare undertakings are 
also incorporated into this project. 
  After the signing agreement, Premier Li Peng and his wife 
Zhu 
Lin met with Premier Goh Chok Tong, Senior Minister Lee Kuan 
Yew, and his wife He Yu Zhi. 
  Li Peng said the decision by the two governments to 
cooperate 
in building the Suzhou industrial park constitutes a major event 
in bilateral ties. This has provided a new pattern for and 
injected new ingredients into the economic cooperation between 
the two countries, Li Peng noted, adding that it is of positive 
significance in the deepening of the friendly and cooperative 
relations between the two countries. 
  Li Peng expressed welcome to Premier Goh Chok Tong and 
Senior 
Minister Lee Kuan Yew on their current visit to China and called 
them old friends of the Chinese people. He praised them for 
doing a lot of beneficial work to promote the development of the 
friendly and cooperative relations between China and Singapore. 
In the past two years, Li Peng said, the relations between 
China and Singapore have been developing smoothly and the two 
countries have conducted effective cooperation in various 
spheres. 
  The conclusion of the agreement in a relatively short period 
of time demonstrates both sides' sincerity for cooperation, Li 
Peng said, adding that there will of course be much to be done 
after the agreement is signed. 
  Li Peng said the Suzhou-Wuxi-Changzhou area is a place 
propitious for giving birth to great men, with a favorable 
investment environment and labor of good quality. He expressed 
the belief that with the support of the two governments and 
close coordination between relevant departments of both bides, 
the industrial park will surely achieve fruitful results. 
  Li Peng also briefed the guests on China's economic 
development last year and so far this year as well as on China's 
current reform measures on monetary, taxation, finance, and 
investment structures. He said that since last year, the country 
has experienced an unprecedented excellent momentum in 
attracting foreign investment, with the greater part of foreign 
investment going to basic industry and the sphere of investment 
expanded into tertiary industry. China is opening its market 
even wider to the outside world, Li Peng said, adding that it 
welcomes cooperation of every kind with entrepreneurs and 
financiers from Singapore and other countries. 
  Goh Chok Tong and the other honorable guests arrived in 
Beijing this afternoon. During the meeting, he said he was 
pleased to have the opportunity of making a working visit to 
China, of attending the signing ceremony of the Suzhou 
industrial park, and of meeting with Premier Li Peng. The 
signing of the agreement on the Suzhou Industrial Park reflects 
the common aspirations of the two sides and marks a new 
development in bilateral economic cooperation, Goh said. 
Singapore hopes the park will yield concrete fruit soon after 
beginning operations and that it is willing to make joint 
efforts to this end with the Chinese side, Goh said. 
  Also in the afternoon, the two sides signed an agreement on 
the adoption of Singapore's economic and public administration 
experience. Vice Premier Li Lanqing and Senior Minister Lee 
Kuan Yew attended the signing ceremony. 
  Under this agreement, Suzhou Municipality will borrow 
Singapore's successful experience in the areas of economic 
development, urban planning and construction and management, as 
well as other public administration management in the 
construction and development of the Suzhou Industrial Park. 
  In the evening, a consolidated commercial agreement for the 
industrial park was signed. Jiangsu Governor Chen Huanyou and 
Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew attended the signing ceremony. 

</TEXT>

