<H3> <TI>   People's Bank of China Delegation Meets With SRV Leaders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2602225094 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0834 
GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2602225094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Hu Suojin (5170 6956 6930)] </F>
  [Text] Hanoi, 22 Feb (XINHUA) -- Do Muoi, general secretary 
of the Communist Party of Vietnam [CPV], SRV President Le Duc 
Anh, SRV Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet, and CPV Central Committee 
adviser Pham Van Dong met separately with the visiting Chen 
Yuan, vice governor of the People's Bank of China, and his party 
on 21 and 22 February. 
  During the meeting, Do Muoi stressed that it is very 
necessary for Vietnam and China to expand and strengthen their 
cooperation in all fields of endeavor. 
  Do Muoi said: Science and technology have enjoyed rapid 
development in China in recent years. China's machinery 
equipment is very suitable for Vietnam. At present, economic 
construction is the central task of various work in Vietnam. 
Vietnam and China should seize the opportunity and should 
successfully conduct trade and economic cooperation as quickly 
as possible. It is beneficial for both countries. 
  Do Muoi also spoke highly of Comrade Deng Xiaoping's theory 
on building socialism with Chinese characteristics as well as of 
the successes achieved by China in economic reform. 
  During the meeting, Le Duc Anh stated that developing 
friendly Vietnamese-Chinese relations is in keeping with the 
historical trend and is a necessity as a result of the 
development of the situation. He expressed the hope that banks 
of the two countries will strengthen cooperation, and he 
expressed his support for the two countries' further developing 
trade and economic relations. 
  During the meeting, Chen Yuan said: China and Vietnam have 
tremendous potential for trade and economic cooperation. 
Chinese and Vietnamese banks exchanged views during the 
delegation's visit on the reform of the banking system and 
unanimously agreed to strengthen cooperation between themselves. 
  The People's Bank of China delegation led by Chen Yuan 
arrived in Hanoi on 19 February for a week-long visit at the 
invitation of the State Bank of Vietnam. The delegation is 
scheduled to leave Hanoi this afternoon for Ho Chi Minh City to 
continue its visit. 

</TEXT>

