<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Activities of Premier Li Peng </TI></H3>
<H4>   Celebrates Lantern Festival </H4>
<F P=102> OW2502191494 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1516 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2502191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporters Duanmu Laidi (4551 2606 0171 1229) and Gao </F>
Jianxin (7559 1696 2450)] 
  [Text] Beijing, 25 Feb (XINHUA) -- Premier Li Peng and his 
wife Zhu Lin, Vice Premiers Zou Jiahua and Li Lanqing, and other 
leading comrades joined members of the Preliminary Working 
Committee [PWC] of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region 
Preparatory Committee this evening to mark the Lantern Festival 
held at the Hong Kong and Macao Center. 
  The center, which is located on the second floor of a 
building on the East 40th Street, was decorated with lanterns 
and colorful streamers and was permeated with laughter this 
evening. The get-together sponsored by PWC members from Hong 
Kong opened at 1830 [1030 GMT] under the chairmanship of Zhu 
Youlin, a PWC member from Hong Kong, and Ni Ping, a celebrated 
presenter from China Central Television. After PWC Vice 
Chairman An Zijie gave a welcoming speech, Premier Li Peng gave 
an extemporaneous speech. He said he was very glad to be able 
to join PWC members from Hong Kong in marking the Lantern 
Festival, and he wished all PWC members good health, successful 
careers, and happiness for their families. 
  Speaking on the current situation in Hong Kong, Li Peng 
said: 
The China today is not the China of more than 150 years ago. 
Today, China's political situation is stable, its economy is 
developing, and we are full of confidence in the future of our 
motherland. He said: No matter what may happen, the Chinese 
Government's determination to reinstate its sovereignty over 
Hong Kong will not change, and Hong Kong certainly will witness 
a stable transition of political power and long-term prosperity 
and stability. 
  Under the current circumstances, Li Peng said, the PWC's 
burdens and responsibilities have become even heavier and 
greater. He urged all PWC members to work harder and make even 
greater contributions to Hong Kong's long-standing stability and 
prosperity and the motherland's prosperity. 
  The 50 or so PWC members from Hong Kong and China, members 
of 
its secretariat, and friends from the press watched a brilliant 
performance given by literary and art workers in the capital. 
The pleasure-filled get-together, which lasted more than two 
hours, reached a climax when Lu Ping, director of the State 
Council's Hong Kong and Macao Office, and Fang-huang Jiwen, a 
PWC member from Hong Kong, sang the songs "I Am A Chinese" and 
"Tomorrow Will Be Even Better." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

