<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hu Jintao Visits Scientists, Educators </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702171094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1508 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2702171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 27 (XINHUA) -- Hu Jintao, member 
of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central 
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, visited a group of 
senior scientists and educators in Beijing early today. 
  Taking part in a voluntary program sponsored by the Central 
Committee of the Chinese Communist League and All-China 
Federation of the Youth League, Hu first went to see Wang 
Dingfang, a 64-year-old nuclear scientist. 
  The program enlists the help of many young people including 
young medical workers who render volunteer services to senior 
scientists and educators in their homes. 
  Hu said that it is one of the important policies of the 
party 
to respect knowledge and respect talents. 
  He assured Wang that the party and the government will make 
efforts to improve the working and living conditions for 
scientists. 
  At the house of Lu Qing, deputy director of the Space 
Research Center of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, he noted 
that senior officials and scientists have made great 
contributions to the revolution and that young people should 
render services to them. 
  He said that the volunteer services to the elderly 
contribute 
to upholding fine Chinese traditions. 
  At the home of Xi Lu, a 77-year-old chemistry teacher at 
Beijing No. 47 High School, Hu said that the time and the 
society call for the volunteer services from the youth to the 
senior intellectuals and model workers. 
  He said that the volunteer service spirit should be 
encouraged so as to promote fine social conduct and customs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

