<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC To Launch Communications Satellite </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802092794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0814 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 28 (XINHUA) -- The China Great 
Wall Industry Corporation (CGWIC) and the U.S. Hughes 
Communications International, Inc. signed a contract here today 
for the launching of the Optus B3 communications satellite. 
  Liu Zhixiong, deputy-president of the CGWIC, said that Optus 
B3 will be sent into space aboard a Long March 2e launch vehicle 
at the Xichang satellite launch center in Sichuan Province in 
the second half of this year. 
  Liu said that the launch services contract was finalized by 
both parties after more than one year of discussions and joint 
efforts. 
  In addition, both parties also signed a long-term 
co-operation agreement today for the launching of an additional 
ten Hughes-built communications satellites in the coming 12 
years. 
  Hughes is a well-known manufacturer of communications 
satellites, occupying some 60 percent of the worldwide 
commercial communications satellite market. It was one of the 
earliest Western satellite manufacturers to do business with the 
CGWIC. Its products, Asiasat-1 and an Australian-owned 
communications satellite, have already been successfully 
launched by the CGWIC. 
  The two sides have contracted to launch the Hughes-built 
Apstar-1 and Apstar-2, as well as the Optus B3 this year, and 
hope to extend their co-operation in the space field in the near 
future. 

</TEXT>

