<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Views Qian Qichen's Bangladesh Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Signs Loan Agreement </H4>
<F P=102> OW2602180194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1707 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2602180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dhaka, February 26 (XINHUA) -- China is to provide 
Bangladesh with a 8.5 million U.S. dollars interest-free loan in 
1994 as a governmental financial assistance to this South Asian 
nation. 
  This was confirmed by an agreement signed on Saturday [26 
February] by visiting Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen and 
Bangladesh Finance Minister M. Saifur Rahman. 
  The usage of the loan is to be decided between the two sides 
later this year, according to Chinese sources. 
  Since the diplomatic relation between the two countries was 
established in 1975, remarkable progress has been made in trade 
and economy as well as many other fields. 
  The two sides have expressed their hopes to expand the 
friendly relations, especially in trade and economic sector. 
  Qian, who is on an official goodwill visit to Bangladesh, is 
scheduled to leave for Sri Lanka on Sunday. 
  Bangladesh is the second leg of his five-nation trip which 
also includes Pakistan, Maldives and Iran. 

</TEXT>

