<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Views Qian Qichen's Bangladesh Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Discusses Tibet </H4>
<F P=102> OW2702232994 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1354 
GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2702232994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dhaka, 27 Feb (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice Premier and 
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen held a news conference in the 
(Podema) State Guesthouse here today. He answered reporters' 
questions about the international and regional situation and 
China's relations with South Asian nations. 
  Replying to a question on the idea of a nuclear-free zone in 
South Asia, Qian Qichen pointed out: The domestic situations in 
most South Asian countries are stabilizing. The relations among 
countries in the region have been improving, and regional 
cooperation is also being developed. However, there are still 
some destabilizing factors in South Asia. There are still some 
differences among the countries of the region. He said: China 
supports the proposition of a South Asia nuclear-free zone. 
China also hopes that an arms race would not occur in the 
region. An arms race will not benefit peace and stability in 
the region. 
  On Sino-Indian relations, Qian Qichen said: Since the 
normalization of Sino-Indian relations, we have been satisfied 
with the development of bilateral relations. We hold that the 
development of Sino-Indian relations should by no means affect 
China's friendly cooperation with other countries in the region. 
We hope that the development of Sino-Indian relations will aid 
the development of China's cooperative relations with South Asia 
as a whole. 
  Qian Qichen emphasized: Tibet is an inalienable part of 
China's territory, and the Indian Government has more than once 
openly acknowledged this fact. China hopes that India will 
handle some existing questions in accordance with this principle. 
  As regards the Kashmir issue, Qian Qichen said: China's 
policy on the issue remains unchanged. China hopes that India 
and Pakistan can resolve the problem through friendly and 
peaceful negotiations in accordance with the United Nation's 
resolutions and the relevant agreements reached between the two 
countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

