<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Arrives in Sri Lanka </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2802134294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1308 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2802134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colombo, February 28 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice 
Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen arrived here this 
evening on a two-day official goodwill visit to Sri Lanka. 
  Qian came here after his visits to Pakistan and Bangladesh. 
Sri Lanka is the third country of his five-nation tour which 
will also take him to the Maldives and Iran. 
  He was greeted by Sri Lankan Foreign Minister A.C.S. Hameed 
and Chinese Ambassador to Sri Lanka Zhang Chengli at the Colombo 
airport. 
  In a written statement issued at the airport, Qian said, 
"China and Sri Lanka have been enjoying a profound traditional 
friendship which goes back to ancient times." 
  He noted that "over the past 30 years or more since the 
establishment of the diplomatic relations, the friendly 
relations and cooperation between the two countries have 
developed satisfactorily." 
  He expressed the hope that his current visit "will help 
enhance mutual understanding, deepen friendship and promote 
cooperation between the two countries." 
  He said he is looking forward to an in-depth exchange of 
views with his Sri Lankan counterpart Hameed on bilateral 
relations and regional and international issues of mutual 
interest. 
  Qian is expected to call on Sri Lankan President D.B. 
Wijetunge and Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe during his 
visit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

