<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Articles View New Shares Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   No `A' Shares Sales to Foreigners </H4>
<F P=102> OW2502144094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1404 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 25 (XINHUA) -- China's securities 
authorities today overruled a Shanghai share-holding company's 
plan to turn part of the "A" shares it has issued to foreign 
investors into "B" shares. 
  "No such transformation of shares will be permitted until a 
relevant policy is worked out," said a spokesman of the China 
Securities Regulatory Committee (CSRC) at a press conference 
here today. 
  Stocks issued by Chinese firms fall into two categories: A 
shares for domestic investors and B shares for overseas 
investors. The two kinds of shares are traded at different 
markets and follow different trading rules. 
  The CSRC spokesman said that the board of "Dazhong" Taxi 
Company obviously has little knowledge about state securities 
policies. 
  He said that opening "A" shares to foreigners means both the 
sell-out of state property rights and the merger of the two 
kinds of shares, which is something "under serious consideration 
of the authorities," and if so, requires amendment of the 
current laws and regulations on stock market monitoring. 
  "A grassroots company has no right to make the decision 
without state permission," the spokesman said. 
  He said that a tentative distribution plan for the 5.5 
billion yuan worth of nationwide stocks to be issued for 1994 
has been made. 
  Timing of the issuance will be flexible and will depend upon 
the conditions of enterprises as well as the capacity of the 
stock market to absorb the new stocks, he said. 
  According to the spokesman, it is very likely that part of 
the stock issuance will be postponed until next year. 

</TEXT>

