<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cotton Procurement Price Increases Substantially </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2802060094 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 1044 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2802060094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 25 Feb (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE) -- China has 
decided to raise the cotton procurement price by a large margin 
as of 1 September 1994 when newly harvested cotton is to be sold 
on the market. The price for standard ginned cotton is to be 
raised from 330 yuan to about 400 yuan per 50 kg. In addition, 
some cotton producing provinces also will introduce some other 
preferential measures to encourage peasants to grow cotton. 
  Cotton output slumped in 1993 owing to natural disasters and 
other factors. Statistics by the end of January this year 
indicate that the country's total cotton procurement was only 67 
percent of the procurement for the same period last year. 
Hebei, Shandong, and Henan -- the major cotton producing 
provinces of China the cotton output of which used to account 
for half of the country's total cotton output -- witnessed the 
greatest decrease margin in cotton production which has directly 
affected the country's cotton procurement as a whole. 
  To ease the grim situation in cotton production and 
marketing, and to encourage peasants to grow cotton, the state 
now has decided to raise the cotton procurement price by about 
21 percent this year, in addition to the 10-percent price rise 
last year. Meanwhile, the amount of subsidies to cotton growers 
also will be increased appropriately to make up the price 
difference between parity and the negotiated prices for chemical 
fertilizers and diesel oil. This will be another round of 
substantial raises in the cotton procurement price in China 
after a series of price rises over the past few years since 1988. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

